CFC Kansas City, April 16/88
C.B&L.RR.
Sir:
In continuation of the above operation
My operator G.F.G. further reports as follows: 
Saturday, April 14/88 - "I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. and proceeded to the [?Amire} Depot. Upon my arrival at the depot I strolled through the yards and conversed with the employees and found that they apprehended no further trouble at present. The idea heretofore unclear that the Brotherhood was unclear is gradually wearing away and some think that the strikers will have to succeed The new men on the switch engines are becoming more familiar with the yards and consequently there is not so much grumbling among the switchmen as when they first come out. Noticing a policeman
Completed

on a Hannibal engine I said to a switchman: "I see that the new men still have a body guard." His reply was: "Yes, I - unclear, they need them too" A policemen on a "2" engine is no figurehead. He is an actual necessity and will be for some time." 
Everything was quiet and orderly about the yards and I saw nor heard nothing that would lead me to suspect further trouble at present." 
My operator H.E. reports as follows: 
Thursday, April 12/88
"At 3 p.m. I left the Agency for the purpose of getting such information as W.H Courtney, a patrolman on Capt. McGraw's force was reports to have concurring the assault that was made upon two of the employees of the C.B. & 2 RR in the Whittakers restaurant the morning of April 1st. I called upon Capt. McGraw but did not find him at his office. I saw his clerk and informed him of the business I was upon. He informed me the patrolman Courtney would not report until late in the evening.
Completed

but when he did he (the clerk) would learn all he could from him relation to what he might know fo the assault. i then as per appointment proceeded to the Union Depot and called at the office of Mr. Fish. He not being in I waited until nearly 5 p.m. On his not returning I returned to the Agency and at 6:30 p.m. I again called at the office of Capt. McGraw. I saw the clerk. He informed me he had seen Officer Courtney and he had said he did not see the assault, but he believe he  could identify the man, as this was not in accordance with his assertions. I asked the clerk to request Capt. McGraw to speak to Courtney and endeavor to get all the information he could from him. I arranged to call again and see the Capt. I then returned to the Agency." 
My Operator G.F.G. further reports: 
Sunday, April 15th/88
"I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. and proceeded to Union Depot. After arriving at the depot I walked through the yards and found every-
Completed

thing quiet and orderly. In conversing with the switchmen I find that they remember how the striking engineers acted during the switchmens' strike some time since. The switchmen claim that the switch engineers at that time instead of attending strictly to their own line of business also performed the duties of the switchmen. Many railroad men think the unclear stand taken by the "2" road in the present contest will be a great help towards preventing railroad strikes in the future. They also think that had the company yielded to the demands of the strikers trouble would be likely to occur in other departments during the summer. There is a growing belief that the strikers will, before a great while, come back and ask to be re-instated in their former positions and agree to the terms and conditions that the company has dictated." 
Yours respectfully,
Pinkertons Natl. Detective Agency
W.A. Pinkerton
unclear Supt. W.D.

Kansas City, April 17/88
C.B. & 2. R.R. C.F.C.
Sir: 
In continuation of the above operation
My operative C.F.C further reports as follows: 
Monday, April 16th/88- 
"I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. adn proceeded to the Union Depot for the purpose of gathering such facts as would be of interest to the company. Upon my arrival I found everything quiet about the yards. many with whom I conversed think that if labor organizations were as united and as willing to pull together corporations are that they would have better chances of success. They also think that until they can get legislation favorable to the laboring classes they will be abliged to submit to the demands of the corporations. I learned no new feature concerning the
Completed

strike. There is very little talk about it and no excitement whatever. I mixed with the railroad men and remained about the different rendezvous and noticed that there was an evident uneasy feeling amongst them. They have very little to say and all are in hopes of something may happen to give them a chance to go back to work and return in a way that won't be humiliating. They don't seem to know how they stand. Dissections are breeding They are looking for some turn that will be advantageous to them."
Yours respectfully,
Pinkerton's Nat'l Detection Agency
W.A. Pinkerton
Gen'l Supt W.D.
Completed

Kansas City, April 18/88
C.B. & 2. R.R.  C.F.C.
Sir: 
In continuation of the above operation
My Operative C.F.C. further reports as follows: 
Tuesday, April 17th/88
"I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m-
Upon my arrival at the depot I found it quiet about the yards, although there had been some damage dome during the night by the strikes or their sympathizers. The switchmen and other employees are unclear about the affair and don't seem to want to talk much about it. They declare boys are doing the mischief and the blame is thrown on them. In conversation with one of the strikers he said: "The newspapers made a big thing out of what occurred and anything that happens to cause an accident which
Completed

is the result of carelessness. The railroad company claim it is done to wreck. There's no use talking, the railroad company had won this time and it's foolish to think otherwise. We are beat, and its through bad management on the part of Arthur and Stevens. The next time we'll show more strength." 
Muller was very busy to-day but I could not learn what it was about. At 7 p.m. I discontinued." 
Yours respectfully
Pinkerton's Nat'l Detection Agency
W.A. Pinkerton
Gen'l Supt. W.D.
Completed

Kansas City April 19/88
C.B. & 2. R.R.  C.F.C. 
Sir: 
In continuation of the above operation
My Operative C.F.C. further reports as follows: 
Wednesday, April 18/88: 
"I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. Upon my arrival at the depot I found people in groups discussing the features of the switchmans "lay off." I heard nothing of importance to the company. After the strike was settled and the men resumed work the crowd dispersed and everything was comparatively quiet during the afternoon. I hear an occasional allusion to the "scabs." The men were attending to their work with regularity and everything was orderly and quiet at 6 o'clock p.m. when I returned to the Agency. Yours respectfully,
Pinkerton's Nat'l Detective Agency
W.A. Pinkerton
Genl Supt W.D.
Completed

Kansas City, April 20th/88
C.B.&2.R.R.  C.F.C.
Sir: 
In continuation of the above operation
My Operative C.F.C. further reports as follows: 
Thursday, April 19/88
"I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. Upon my arrival at the depot I found everything in quietness. In talking with a striking engineer to-day he stated that although the company had money and law on its side, it cannot have everything its own way. He said that he did not unclear violence, but still if a little were perpetuated occasionally it was not so bad, so long as it did not injure any innocent person, but he did not consider "scabs" innocent people. I was also talking with a switchman  who said that they were cautioned about talking too
Completed

much with outsiders. he stated during the conversation that something might occur when the people least expected it. He also said that he talked too much sometimes when he had taken a few "beers." I think that there is a greater liability of trouble during the first week after pay day. Everything quiet at 6 p.m. when I left that vicinity and returned to the Agency." 
Yours respectfully,
Pinkerton's Nat'l Detective Agency
W.A. Pinkerton
Genl. Supt. W.D.
